com.apriori.collections

Class AbstractNavigableMap.SubMap

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.apriori.collections.AbstractNavigableMap<K,V>
      • com.apriori.collections.AbstractNavigableMap.SubMap
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Map<K,V>, java.util.NavigableMap<K,V>, java.util.SortedMap<K,V>
    Enclosing class:
    AbstractNavigableMap<K,V>

    protected class AbstractNavigableMap.SubMap
extends AbstractNavigableMap<K,V>
    A sub-map view, with bounds on the range of included keys. This implementation defines its operations in terms of operations on the main map. Sub-classes rarely need to extend this class, but may do so if (for example) they can provide more efficient implementations for some operations.

    For example, overriding the Iterator implementation for a map's AbstractNavigableMap.navigableKeySet() can often be done more efficiently (depending on the exact data structures used). If it is overridden in the main map implementation (likely by extending AbstractNavigableMap.KeySet and overriding the map's AbstractNavigableMap.navigableKeySet() method) then it is also prudent to extend this class and override in the same way so that sub-map views can also take advantage of the faster implementation.

      • size

        public int size()

        This implementation actually counts the number of entries within the sub-map's bounds using the AbstractNavigableMap.entrySet()'s iterator. This runs in linear time, O(n), but the result is memo-ized between calls. It will only count the number of entries again if it detects that the main map's AbstractNavigableMap.modCount has changed since the last time the entries were counted.

      • put

        public V put(K key,
             V value)

        This checks if the key is in range and throws an IllegalArgumentException if not. If it is in range, then the main map's put(Object, Object) method is called.

      • putAll

        public void putAll(java.util.Map<? extends K,? extends V> m)

        This default implementation simply loops over all entries in the specified map and calls Map.put(Object, Object) for each one.

        This checks that if all keys in the specified map are in range and throws an IllegalArgumentException if any of them are not. If all keys are in range, then the main map's putAll(Map) method is called.

      • clear

        public void clear()
        Removes all elements within the sub-map's bounds.

        This uses the same implementation as the default. It also updates its memo-ized size to zero (so size() will not need to count elements unless items are actually added to the map).

      • headMap

        public java.util.NavigableMap<K,V> headMap(K toKey,
                                           boolean inclusive)
        Provides a new view of the head of this sub-map. If the specified upper bound is not within this sub-map's bounds then a IllegalArgumentException is thrown. This delegates to the main map's implementation after range-checking the specified bound.

        If this sub-map has no lower bound, then the main map's headMap(Object, boolean) method is used. If this sub-map does have a lower bound, then the main map's subMap(Object, boolean, Object, boolean) method is used and supplied this sub-map's lower bound and the specified upper bound.

      • lowerEntry

        public java.util.Map.Entry<K,V> lowerEntry(K key)
        Finds the entry in this sub-map with the greatest key that is less than the specified key. This first calls the main map's implementation of lowerEntry(Object). If it is not null then it is range checked and returned if within the sub-map's bounds. If it is less than the sub-map's lower bound then null is returned. If it is greater than the sub-map's upper bound, then the sub-map's lastEntry() is returned.

If it is greater than the sub-map's upper bound, then the sub-map's lastEntry() is returned.

      • higherEntry

        public java.util.Map.Entry<K,V> higherEntry(K key)
        Finds the entry in this sub-map with the smallest key that is greater than the specified key. This first calls the main map's implementation of higherEntry(Object).       • firstEntry

        public java.util.Map.Entry<K,V> firstEntry()
        Finds the entry in the map with the smallest key or null if the sub-map is empty. If the sub-map has no lower bound, the main map's first entry is queried. If the sub-map's lower bound is inclusive, then this finds the entry using the main map's ceilingEntry(Object) method and passing the lower bound. If exclusive, the main map's higherEntry(Object) method is used instead. If the resulting entry is non-null and within the sub-map's bounds then it is returned. If, however, it is null or greater than the sub-map's upper bound, null is returned.

      • lastEntry

        public java.util.Map.Entry<K,V> lastEntry()
        Finds the entry in the map with the greatest key or null if the sub-map is empty. If the sub-map has no upper bound, the main map's last entry is queried. If the sub-map's upper bound is inclusive, then this finds the entry using the main map's floorEntry(Object) method and passing the upper bound. If exclusive, the main map's lowerEntry(Object) method is used instead. If the resulting entry is non-null and within the sub-map's bounds then it is returned. If, however, it is null or less than the sub-map's lower bound, null is returned.

      • getModCount

        protected int getModCount()
        Returns the main map's modification count. This allows iterators over sub-map views to properly fail-fast.

        Since a AbstractNavigableMap.SubMap extends AbstractNavigableMap, it also inherits a AbstractNavigableMap.modCount field. For sub-maps, that field is compared to the main maps' value to detect when the sub-map's memo-ized size is stale and elements need to be counted.

        Overrides:
        getModCount in class AbstractNavigableMap<K,V>
        Returns:
        the map's modification count
